{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.03,0.02,0.04,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50568"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35787"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11360"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50568"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 47-year-old woman presents with severe left flank pain. She does not take any medications. On examination her blood pressure is 98/72 mmHg, pulse 102/min, temperature 39.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 22/min. She is tender in the left flank. A CT scan shows a 12mm stone in the upper left ureter, together with hydronephrosis of that kidney. She is given 4L isotonic saline and transferred to the intensive care unit for stabilisation prior to surgical intervention. The following arterial blood gas is obtained 4 hours after admission:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.26 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpO2 82 mmHg (\u0026gt;75)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 39 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3- 16 (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa+ 147 (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EK+ 3.9 (3.5-5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECl- 119 (100-109)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this blood gas?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation","Respiratory acidosis with metabolic compensation","Metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation","Respiratory acidosis with no compensation","Mixed metabolic and respiratory acidosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is suffering severe urosepsis and is acutely unwell. Her pH demonstrates acidosis and a low bicarbonate suggests metabolic acidosis. The anticipated compensation for this derangement is a respiratory alkalosis (i.e. low pCO2) - however this patient\u0027s pCO2 is inappropriately normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn metabolic acidosis, respiratory compensation can be expected to occur within 30 - 120 minutes. The absence of an appropriate secondary response in a sufficient timeframe indicates an additional co-existing acid-base disorder, often referred to as a \u0027mixed picture\u0027, more specifically a \u003Cstrong\u003Emixed metabolic and respiratory acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe expected pCO2 in metabolic acidosis (within a \u00b12 range) can be estimated using Winter\u0027s formula: Anticipated pCO2 = 1.5 x [bicarb] + 8 (\u00b12). In this case, the expected pCO2 for her metabolic acidosis would be: 1.5 x 16 + 8 = 32 (\u00b12); versus the patient\u0027s actual pCO2 which is 39. Given sufficient time has elapsed for compensation to occur, the lack of this secondary response indicates that a co-existing respiratory acidosis is present. Possible causes for the patient\u0027s respiratory acidosis include inadequate ventilation secondary to pain or developing respiratory failure secondary to fatigue. Additionally, the patient could have undiagnosed respiratory conditions that limit her ability to appropriately compensate however this is less likely given the stem. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient\u0027s blood gas had been taken within 2 hours of onset of her acidosis, the picture could be characterised as metabolic acidosis with no compensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lack of an appropriate compensatory respiratory alkalosis indicates this is not \u003Cstrong\u003Emetabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence of an alkalosis (pH \u0026gt; 7.45), so \u003Cstrong\u003Emetabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe arterial blood gas does not demonstrate a primary respiratory acidosis. In a primary respiratory acidosis, the pCO2 would be elevated (\u0026gt; 45 mmHg). Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory acidosis with no compensation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory acidosis with metabolic compensation \u003C/strong\u003Eare incorrect. The low HCO3- of 16 mmol/L confirms a metabolic acidosis rather than compensation for a respiratory acidosis. Metabolic compensation (elevated HCO3-) would not be expected to occur to a significant extent in the acute setting in any case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Even with a clear metabolic or respiratory picture consider the other values and be wary of an inappropriately normal result"],"references":["Adrogu\u00e9 HJ, Madias NE. Secondary responses to altered acid-base status: the rules of engagement. J Am Soc Nephrol. 2010 Jun;21(6):920-3.","Brandi, K. Acid Base Physiology. August 2015, Accessed May 19 2024, https://www.anaesthesiamcq.com/AcidBaseBook/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35787"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35787"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-13T19:20:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T10:57:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2357"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50568"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"